---
import { Code } from "astro:components";
import BlogPostLayout from "../../../components/BlogPostLayout.astro";
import { blogPostStaticPaths, type BlogPostMetadata } from "../../../blog/types";
import { defaultLocale, localePath, type Locale } from "../../../i18n/utils";

export const metadata: BlogPostMetadata = {
  title: "Zero-Code Validations in Your .NET API",
  summary:
    "How swapping primitive strings and ints for Kalicz.StrongTypes turned request validation into something the JSON deserializer and the compiler do for me — less code, honest signatures, and far fewer edge cases to test.",
  pubDate: "2026-07-04",
  tags: ["dotnet", "csharp", "strong-types", "api-design"],
};

export const getStaticPaths = () => blogPostStaticPaths(metadata);

const lang = (Astro.params.lang ?? defaultLocale) as Locale;

const codeThemes = { light: "github-light", dark: "github-dark" } as const;

const beforeSnippet = `public record CreateOrderRequest(string CustomerEmail, string ProductCode, int Quantity);

[HttpPost]
public IActionResult Create(CreateOrderRequest request)
{
    if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(request.CustomerEmail))
        return BadRequest("Customer email is required.");
    if (!MailAddress.TryCreate(request.CustomerEmail, out _))
        return BadRequest("Customer email is not valid.");
    if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(request.ProductCode))
        return BadRequest("Product code is required.");
    if (request.Quantity <= 0)
        return BadRequest("Quantity must be positive.");

    // ...four checks later, the actual work finally starts.
}`;

const afterSnippet = `public record CreateOrderRequest(Email CustomerEmail, NonEmptyString ProductCode, Positive<int> Quantity);

[HttpPost]
public IActionResult Create(CreateOrderRequest request)
{
    // An invalid payload never reaches this line. The built-in
    // System.Text.Json converters already rejected it with a 400.
    var order = orders.Place(request.CustomerEmail, request.ProductCode, request.Quantity);
    return Ok(order);
}`;

const signatureSnippet = `// Before: every caller re-checks, every reader wonders.
Order Place(string email, string code, int quantity);

// After: the signature is the contract.
Order Place(Email email, NonEmptyString code, Positive<int> quantity);`;

const resultSnippet = `public Result<Order, PlaceOrderError> Place(Email email, NonEmptyString code, Positive<int> quantity)
{
    if (!catalog.Contains(code))
        return PlaceOrderError.UnknownProduct;

    return new Order(email, code, quantity);
}`;

const constructionSnippet = `NonEmptyString name = NonEmptyString.Create(input);   // throws on invalid
NonEmptyString? safe = NonEmptyString.TryCreate(input); // null on invalid
NonEmptyString? fluent = input.AsNonEmpty();             // same, as an extension`;
---

<BlogPostLayout metadata={metadata} lang={lang}>
  <p>
    A while ago I reviewed an endpoint that was, by every checklist, done. It compiled, it had tests, it even had XML docs. It also spent
    its first fifteen lines interrogating its own request object: is the email set, does it parse, is the product code blank, is the
    quantity at least one. The actual business logic — the reason the endpoint exists — started somewhere around line twenty.
  </p>

  <p>
    That's not an unusual endpoint. That's most endpoints. When a request DTO is made of <code>string</code> and
    <code>int</code>, every field is a liar until proven otherwise, and the proving is on you — in the controller, then again in the service
    that doesn't quite trust the controller, then again in the domain that doesn't quite trust either of them.
  </p>

  <Code code={beforeSnippet} lang="csharp" themes={codeThemes} />

  <h2>Parse, don't validate</h2>

  <p>
    The fix is an old functional-programming idea: instead of checking values and passing the same loose type along, convert the value <em
      >once</em
    > into a type that cannot represent the invalid state. A <code>string</code> that survived a null check is still a <code>string</code> — the
    check's result is thrown away the moment it passes. A
    <code>NonEmptyString</code> carries the proof in the type, and the compiler enforces it everywhere downstream.
  </p>

  <p>
    That's what my <a href={localePath(lang, "strong-types")}>Kalicz.StrongTypes</a> package packages up for C#: a small set of validated wrappers
    — <code>NonEmptyString</code>, <code>Email</code>, <code>Positive&lt;T&gt;</code> and friends over any <code>INumber&lt;T&gt;</code>, <code
      >NonEmptyEnumerable&lt;T&gt;</code
    > — plus the algebraic types
    <code>Maybe&lt;T&gt;</code> and <code>Result&lt;T, TError&gt;</code> to compose them with.
  </p>

  <h2>The zero-code part</h2>

  <p>One line to install:</p>

  <Code code="dotnet add package Kalicz.StrongTypes" lang="shell" themes={codeThemes} />

  <p>Then the request record swaps its primitives for types that mean what they say:</p>

  <Code code={afterSnippet} lang="csharp" themes={codeThemes} />

  <p>
    The trick is that the package ships <code>System.Text.Json</code> converters that need no registration. When a payload arrives with an empty
    product code or a quantity of zero, deserialization itself fails, and ASP.NET Core turns that into an RFC 7807 <code>400</code> with the offending
    field named — before your endpoint method is ever called. All four guard clauses from the first snippet are gone, and nothing replaced them.
    There is no validator class, no attribute soup, no pipeline behavior. The types <em>are</em> the validation.
  </p>

  <h2>Signatures become documentation</h2>

  <p>
    The part I didn't anticipate when I started writing the package is how far the effect travels beyond the API boundary. Once the edge
    parses values into strong types, every layer below it gets to state its real requirements:
  </p>

  <Code code={signatureSnippet} lang="csharp" themes={codeThemes} />

  <p>
    The second signature answers questions the first one forces you to research: no, the email can't be null; no, zero quantity can't happen
    here; yes, you can pass this straight to the persistence layer. Reviewers stop asking "what if this is empty?" because the question no
    longer type-checks.
  </p>

  <p>
    Business rules that <em>can</em> legitimately fail get the same treatment with <code>Result&lt;T, TError&gt;</code> — failure becomes a value
    in the signature instead of a surprise exception:
  </p>

  <Code code={resultSnippet} lang="csharp" themes={codeThemes} />

  <h2>Fewer edge cases, fewer tests</h2>

  <p>
    My favorite consequence is what happens to the test suite. The tests that fed <code>null</code>, <code>""</code>,
    <code>" "</code> and <code>-1</code> into every layer to verify each one defends itself? Deleted. Those states are unrepresentable, so there
    is nothing to defend against. What remains are tests about behavior — the ones worth reading. At the boundaries where you do construct values
    from loose input, the API is explicit about intent:
  </p>

  <Code code={constructionSnippet} lang="csharp" themes={codeThemes} />

  <p>
    And for the properties you still want to verify, the <code>Kalicz.StrongTypes.FsCheck</code> companion package generates valid strong-typed
    values for property-based tests, so your generators respect the same invariants your code does. There's an EF Core companion with value converters,
    too.
  </p>

  <h2>Try it</h2>

  <p>
    The backend behind this very site runs on StrongTypes end to end — request DTOs, domain events, entity state. If the approach appeals to
    you, the <a href={localePath(lang, "strong-types")}>StrongTypes page</a> has diagrams and more examples, the source lives on
    <a href="https://github.com/KaliCZ/StrongTypes" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">GitHub</a>, and the package is on <a
      href="https://www.nuget.org/packages/Kalicz.StrongTypes"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener noreferrer">NuGet</a
    >. Start with one request record. Delete the guard clauses it makes redundant. You'll know within an afternoon whether you want it
    everywhere.
  </p>
</BlogPostLayout>
